# AKOS AIC Delegation

Use this rule when deciding **which model-seat drives a piece of work** in
Cursor, or when an active model should recommend a seat switch or a subagent
dispatch. It is the *cross-AIC* model-routing policy (consumed by any AIC,
not owned by MADEIRA). Ratified 2026-05-29: model-seat routing is **advisory**
(DQ-TAX-04) and inherits the operator-picks-per-task framing (F5 per
`D-IH-84-C`).

This is **operator-tooling**, not a People canonical — so it may name Opus,
Composer, Codex, subagents, etc. The People-canonical jargon gate
([`akos-people-discipline-of-disciplines.mdc`](akos-people-discipline-of-disciplines.mdc)
RULE 4) does **not** apply here. Doctrine canonicals still get a jargon-free
forward pointer, never model names.

## RULE 1 — Two seats (binding mental model)

- **Foreground thinking seat** (Opus / thinking models): judgment, scope calls,
  doctrine + canonical synthesis, messy multi-part operator input, anything
  irreversible or contested. The operator talks to this seat first.
- **Background execution seats** (Composer-pinned subagents via the Task tool /
  background agents): bounded, well-specified mechanical work — multi-file
  edits, validators, git hygiene, CSV row authoring against a fixed schema.

The plain lookup is the routing-map Layer 0:
[`model-routing-map.md`](../../docs/wip/intelligence/model-selection-2026-05-28/model-routing-map.md).

## RULE 2 — Decompose before delegating (binding)

The thinking seat turns messy operator input into **bounded packets** (files to
touch, validators to run, decision IDs to cite, acceptance check) BEFORE any
heavy execution is dispatched to an execution seat. Dispatching un-decomposed
intent to an execution seat is the most common failure mode — the execution
model pattern-matches instead of verifying. (Worked example: the 2026-05-29
regression where a Composer-authored plan proposed to "mint" a registry that
already existed; the thinking seat caught it. See the paired skill.)

## RULE 3 — Self-detection triggers (advisory)

When an active model detects it is in the wrong seat for the work, it should
**recommend** a switch or a subagent dispatch (it cannot switch the foreground
model itself — see RULE 5):

- **Recommend the thinking seat** when the task involves: doctrine / canonical
  edits, irreversible or commercial decisions, a canonical-CSV gate, a ≥5-file
  refactor whose shape is unclear, or contradictory / multi-threaded input.
- **Recommend dispatching to execution subagents** when the task is: a routine
  CSV transform, a validator run, git hygiene, or a mechanical multi-file edit
  against a settled plan.
- **Stop, do not delegate** when a validator fails, a build breaks, or a
  security / secret concern surfaces — that is a blocker per
  [`akos-baseline-governance.mdc`](akos-baseline-governance.mdc), not a
  delegation decision.

## RULE 4 — Switch back after two misreads (binding)

If an execution seat misreads operator intent **twice in a row**, escalate the
session back to the thinking seat. This is not a new ritual — it reuses the
**knowledge-test cadence** already in the People agentic doctrine
([`HOLISTIKA_AGENTIC_DOCTRINE.md`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/People/canonicals/HOLISTIKA_AGENTIC_DOCTRINE.md)):
repeated misreads are the signal that doctrine absorption has degraded for this
task class, and the thinking seat re-establishes it.

## RULE 5 — The agent can't self-switch; the operator has native per-workflow levers (binding)

Two distinct claims — keep them separate (an earlier draft conflated them):

- **What the agent cannot do (true):** an active model cannot reprogram the
  operator's *foreground* chat model mid-session. This rule stays **advisory** —
  it *recommends* a seat; it does not switch one. Never claim or imply the agent
  auto-switches the foreground model.
- **What the operator CAN do natively (verified 2026-05-29; do not under-state
  this):** Cursor exposes model assignment across exactly the workflows that
  matter — **Agent mode** (model picker + Custom Modes), **Plan mode** (the
  planning-model selector in the input, then *Build Locally* vs *Build in
  parallel*, plus the explore-subagent model in Settings → Subagents), and
  **`/multitask`** (per-subagent `model:` frontmatter in
  `.cursor/agents/<name>.md`; verify it took — early versions fell back to
  inherit). The two-seat split is therefore **operator-configurable**, not merely
  advisory vibes; subagents are one lever, not the only one. Full how-to: the
  paired skill Pattern 3.

## Composition

- Composes with [`akos-operator-communication.mdc`](akos-operator-communication.mdc):
  recommendations use plain functional names first, model codes second.
- The identity context (why a KB-first OS treats the KB as the end and agents as
  its servants) lives in the taxonomy synthesis:
  [`agentic-os-and-aic-taxonomy-2026-05-29/master-synthesis.md`](../../docs/wip/intelligence/agentic-os-and-aic-taxonomy-2026-05-29/master-synthesis.md).
- The existing per-task registry
  ([`MADEIRA_AIC_PER_TASK_REGISTRY.csv`](../../docs/references/hlk/v3.0/Admin/O5-1/People/Compliance/canonicals/dimensions/MADEIRA_AIC_PER_TASK_REGISTRY.csv))
  governs a *different* axis (which AIC, what tools, what permission per task);
  per DQ-TAX-04 it is **not** changed by this advisory rule.

## When this rule does NOT apply

- Inside a People canonical (use a jargon-free pointer instead; never name models).
- For blockers (validator failure, broken build, security) — those follow the
  governance-remediation stop-and-report posture, not delegation.
- For the machine-queryable model-seat-per-task question — that is deferred
  (advisory-only today per DQ-TAX-04; revisit only if a tool needs to FK-resolve
  a model seat).

